The surface morphology, grain size, and shape of the synthesized NPs are evaluated using SEM photographs (Fig. 4
                        ) at different magnifications (10, 5 and 2 μm). The PEO NPs depicted morphology with a bunch of needles resembling grass, at different magnifications as displayed in (Fig. 4(a–c)). Notably, in the absence of BMIM-PF6 IL, a metal–metal bond was formed during NPs synthesis, which increased particle growth and agglomeration [61]. The IL-EO NPs, exposed uniform distribution of needle shaped particles, as depicted in (Fig. 4(d–f)), suggesting the presence of BMIM-PF6 IL functioning as a regulating agent for particle growth through the use of the interaction of ILs. PF6
                        − with Erbium (Er3+), results in decreased NP agglomeration [62]. The BMIM-PF6 IL usage as a templating agent generated IL-EO NPs embedded with tiny needles. However, such needle morphology is a mat that enables it to pass off the cell membrane of microbes, inducing improved antimicrobial action by disrupting microbes phospholipid walls.
